import django_filters
from django_filters import rest_framework as filters
from .models import YourModel  # Replace with your actual model

class YourModelFilter(django_filters.FilterSet):
    id = filters.NumberInFilter(field_name='id', lookup_expr='in')  # Filters for multiple IDs
    name = filters.CharFilter(field_name='name', lookup_expr='exact')  # Exact match for name
    status = filters.CharFilter(field_name='status', lookup_expr='exact')  # Exact match for status
    created_at = filters.DateFilter(field_name='created_at', lookup_expr='gte')  # Filters created after a specific date
    updated_at = filters.DateFilter(field_name='updated_at', lookup_expr='lte')  # Filters updated before a specific date
    price = filters.NumberFilter(field_name='price', lookup_expr='gte')  # Filters for prices greater than or equal to a value

    class Meta:
        model = YourModel  # Replace with your actual model
        fields = ['id', 'name', 'status', 'created_at', 'updated_at', 'price']  # List the fields you want to filter by
